                Supporting End User Development with 
             Visual Programming and Object-Orientation
Workshop of the 7th Conference on Advanced Information Systems Engineering 
                             CAiSE*95

		 13 June 1995, Jyvaskyla, Finland.


The purpose of this workshop is to discuss the possibility and means of
achieving significant advances in end user development by adopting ideas
from visual programming and from business and enterprise object modelling
including object-role modelling, object-oriented databases, workflow
technology, process modelling and so on.

RATIONALE:

End user development, which promises the obvious benefits that can be
obtained from the full utilisation of domain expertise, has often been
criticised for producing ineffective and poorly documented information
systems that are not integrated with the enterprise-wide systems.
Recent advances in software technology such as program generators,
object-oriented programming and visual interface builders such as
Visual Basic have gone some way towards easing the technical problems
of software development.  The application of this technology, however,
is still very limited, and is largely restricted to small projects.
The modelling of higher level processes has not been adequately
addressed nor have problems of enterprise-wide integration.  

The limited application of this technology does not seem to arise from
any inability to overcome fundamental problems and there seems to be
substantial potential for exploiting visual direct-manipulation
techniques at the process level.  These visual techniques should be
related to the set of tasks that a particular user or process manager
performs, thus leveraging this user's domain expertise, interests and
skills.

The development backlog could be tackled by combining end user
development with software reuse.  End user development requires new
programming methods.  The perceived benefits of software reuse have
prompted many companies to rapidly adopt object-oriented ideas both as
a software technology and for modelling.  However, there is the
growing realisation that the object-oriented technology provides only
the enabling mechanisms, and that productive reuse will be possible
only by modelling a business through high-level concepts as business
objects and by object-role modelling techniques.


THE CONFERENCE:

The workshop will be part of the Workshop programme of the CAiSE*95
conference in Jyvaskyla.  This is the 7th conference of series that
has established itself as a truly international event on advanced
information systems engineering.  It gathers researches and
practitioners from academia and industry, giving them opportunity to
discuss and exchange new developments in methods, techniques and
tools.

